AGI - The Israeli army today dismissed the allegations of burying hundreds of Palestinians in a Gaza hospital and claimed to have re-exhumed the bodies to check if there were hostages among them before burying them again. "The accusations that the Israeli Defense Forces (IDF) have buried Palestinian bodies are unfounded," said the army. "During the operation in the Nasser Hospital of Khan Younis, "in an attempt to locate hostages and missing persons, the bodies buried by the Palestinians were carefully examined (...) and only in the places where intelligence services indicated the possible presence of hostages," the army added, ensuring that throughout the procedure "the dignity of the dead" was preserved. "The bodies examined, not being those of the hostages, were reported to their place," he added.
&nbsp;
The Civil Defense of the Gaza Strip declared on Monday that about 200 bodies that had been buried by Israeli forces in common pits at the Nasser hospital in Khan Younis, in the south of the Palestinian territory, were exhumed from Saturday. Some bodies had their hands tied behind their back, he added. The United Nations called for an international investigation into these allegations.> Since the beginning of the war, Gaza hospitals have often been targeted by Israeli military operations, as the basis of the Islamist movement Hamas.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The conflict began on October 7, with an incursion of Islamist militiamen who killed about 1,170 people in southern Israel and kidnapped about 250, according to an AFP count based on Israeli official data. After an exchange of hostages with Palestinian prisoners during a week-long break at the end of November, 129 people were imprisoned in Gaza, 34 of whom would die, according to Israeli officials. The Israeli offensive has so far caused 34.183 deaths, most of which are civilians, according to the Ministry of Health in Gaza, ruled by Hamas since 2007.&nbsp;
