AGI - The European Parliament has given its definitive way to reform the Stability and Growth Pact. One of the most important votes of this legislature, expressed at the last plenary meeting of this mandate. The Italian parties, however, in an unanimous unity have abstained. Excluded the delegation of the 5 star Movement that opted for a clear contradiction. The majority parties - arrived with the responsibility of having negotiated and accepted this Covenant to the Council - did not vote in favour "because they remain many critical points" > . The PD has refrained from approving a pact negotiated by the Meloni> Government. Despite the fact that the European commissioner to the Economy, Paolo Gentiloni.
&nbsp;
The explanation given by the national secretary Elly Schlein over the past few weeks is that this is not the Covenant submitted by the Commission, has been heavily modified by the States on the Council table. "I imagine there are reasons for internal politics," said Gentiloni to journalists who asked him questions about it. "We have joined the Italian policy," he said, referring precisely to the fact that no delegation voted in favour. The Covenant must now be vided to enter into force with a vote by the Council, scheduled for the Council meeting on 29 April. It will be up to agriculture ministers.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The line of the former premier is&nbsp; pragmatic. "It is not perfect and does not solve all problems but it is a good compromise that will allow the EU to prepare better and face economic challenges with renewed confidence." That said, decisions on infringement procedures for excessive deficits will be submitted on 19 June.' And they will almost certainly concern eleven countries, including Italy, which - given yesterday - shows a record deficit for 2023 to 7.4%. "The return plan will not be easy but with the new rules is definitely more compatible than the old ones," said Gentiloni. In conclusion, the reform of the Economic Governance - approved by the Plenary Assembly with 367 votes in favour, 161 against and 69 abstentions - maintains the Maastricht parameters fixing the thresholds of the deficit to 3% of GDP and the debt to 60% >.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Countries with a debt exceeding 90% of GDP will be called to reduce it by a percentage point each year; those with a debt between 60 and 90% will have to reduce it by 0.5%. As regards the deficit, Member States will also have to leave a tax bearing of 1.5% of GDP below the 3% mandatory threshold. Countries in excessive deficit infringement proceedings (over 3%) will be held on annual return plans of 0.5%, always the deficit. The others will however have to reach 1.5% with an annual adjustment that should be 0.4% of GDP (in case of four-year reentry plans), which could be reduced to 0.25% of GDP (in return plans for 7 years). The new provisions are less restrictive than the current requirement that each country should reduce the debt each year of a 20th (5%) of excess exceeding 60%. Governments will be allowed to deviate from the net expenditure path of 0.3% of GDP on an annual basis and 0.6% of GDP cumulatively during the monitoring period. All countries will deliver medium-term plans by 30 September which will align their spending objectives and the ways in which investment and reform will be undertaken. For the 5-star Movement "is a loop around Italian citizens". For the European Greens "is a force shirt to the Member States". &nbsp;
